<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Transport Select Committee: Call for Evidence for “Action for Roads” DRAFT</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">St.Helens</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none"> Council (SRN 007)</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How will the policies set out in the Government’s “Action for Roads” command paper improve the strategic road network for all road users, whilst also improving the environment? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Needs to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recognised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that investment needs to be directed to the whole high</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">way networks as the majority of trips start and end on local highways;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The needs of other road users such as bus and coach does not appear to have much regard</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Recognition of some form of segregation for pedestrians and cyclist on these routes needs to be m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ade</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The policies set out within the Command Paper addresses largely regional traffic, focusing on cars and HGVs in particular. The policy also makes reference to “future proofing” the strategic network for cycling. The policy however does not reference to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or provide any identified investment in the local road network, of which responsibility lies with Local Authorities. It needs to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recognised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that the vast majority of trips either start or end on these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">roads,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and that investment needs to also be directe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d towards supporting maintenance of the rest of the highway network, including associated bridges and other related infrastructure.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The policy does not provide much information regarding other road users, in particular short-bus trips and long-distance co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ach routes which may also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">utilise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the strategic road network as modes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition, as these roads generally operate at high speed (50mph or higher) it is accepted that the roads need to be as safe as possible. This is reflected within the command paper t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o some extent for vehicles and future proofing for cyclists, but little reference is made regarding the potential risk for pedestrian and rights of way related casualties that can occur on the strategic network, in particular at uncontrolled level crossing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s over dual carriageways for rights of way. Due to both vehicular speeds and high risk of fatalities, some form of segregation may be required where possible for hazardous locations, which should be identified within the route based strategies, in particul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ar at locations where high KSI accidents occur.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">By making the best use of the existing highway network through use of selective junction improvements and removing bottlenecks, the policy has the potential to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the environment by mitigating traffic c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ongestion and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">minimising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the need for the provision of entirely new construction.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The form proposed here is similar to that of the rail industry which has been show</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n to work</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The role of Park and Ride should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recognised</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Long terms planning of altern</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ative modes such as rail lines should not be detrimentally affected by highways infrastructure proposals</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The policy need to link with the growth at sea and airports</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">olicy for roads follows a similar policy process for that of rail, with a long term strategy based on five year funding rounds, developed alongside smaller </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Route Based Strategies, which mirrors a similar method of Control Periods and Route </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Utilisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Stra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tegies published by Network Rail. This form of planning has been shown to work within the rail industry, and should potentially work for the development of the highways network.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One of the most direct links to other transport modes is for that of Park and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Ride schemes, both bus and rail orientated. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">siting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> effective Park and ride site will help reduce congestion within towns and cities, and will most likely require being sited next to the strategic highway network to be effective.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">An additional in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">teraction exists relating to the crossing of other transport infrastructure, including rail and canals. Significant planning is required to ensure that any future reinstatement of a rail line for instance is not detrimental and pushed up in cost through th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e development of a new road for instance. In addition, the maintenance or replacement of bridges and removal of level crossings require coordination between both parties to ensure that both modes see an advantage and not cause unnecessary maintenance liabi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lity on one mode.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Finally, the policy needs to link into the proposed growth of both airports and ports, both for the effective and efficient handling of freight and passengers to access these facilities. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How reliable is the Government’s forecast for gr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">owth in demand for the strategic road network? How should the Government deal with uncertainty in its forecast?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Highways Agency must liaise with local authorities on impact of strategic highway network on local development</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Highways Agency needs t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o liaise with local authorities and the City Regions regarding the impact on the strategic highway network of local economic development, of both housing, retail and employment locations, which all may generate additional traffic. This information should t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hen be used to inform the potential traffic growth expected within the area.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Traffic demand on the strategic network is determined by a number of factors that can determine use, and may help inform forecasts. These include:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Locations of economic developm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent and housing sites in proximity to the strategic network</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Demographic indicators, such as car ownership, mode share and travel to work areas</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Public Transport policies and investment, including park and ride (both bus and rail based)</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposals within</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> “Action for Roads” indicates that road funding should be determined in five-year funding rounds. Each funding round should, like the rail industry, focus on delivering specific outputs and ensuring sustainability of the network. Regarding the forecast gro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wth, the funding rounds should collect robust data regarding demand, which can closely monitor the levels of actual demand and adjust accordingly.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How can we improve the reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network? What impact will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">new technology have?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">- The use of system can make capacity improvements with any need for any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cicvils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> work to upgrade a junction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The use of technology is having an increasing role and importance in maintaining the effectiveness of traveling on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strategic road network. This is already demonstrated in the use of “managed motorways” of using the hard shoulder during peak periods, and the deployment of VMS signs to inform road users of delay and disruption.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The wider deployment of this technology </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">across the network will have benefits in terms of both capacity and flexibility at times of disruption. The deployment of technology however is much wider. The deployment for instance of Automatic Number Plate Recognition (ANPR) or Bluetooth opens up possi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bilities of monitoring traffic flows across the network. In addition, enforcement use for uninsured vehicles and speeding could potentially </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">utilise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> these technologies.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">signalised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> junctions, the upgrade of the signals to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">utilise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> MOVA or SCOOT systems pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ovides a chance to provide additional capacity to the road network at pinch points.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What mechanisms are there for Government to increase investment in strategic roads and attract new investors? Are there good examples from other countries that could be ap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">plied in the UK?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whatever mechanism are introduced it is important that these are fully consulted on. New mechanism introduced may increase funding for the strategic road network it is important that this must not be to the detriment and cost of the loc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al Highway Network and the local economy. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How should the Highways Agency be reformed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to make it “the world’s leading highway operator”? What roles should Government and the private sector play to ensure better management of the strategic road network?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iven that the majority of roads in the UK are controlled by Local Highway Authorities any reforms to the Highways Agency should have a role for the Local Highway Authority as part of an assurance framework.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>